  "prompt": "Is using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" grammatically incorrect?",
  "response": "Using \"hairs\" can be grammatically correct but depends on the context. Generally, \"hair\" is an uncountable noun when referring to hair collectively on a person's head or in general. For example, you would say, \"She has beautiful hair.\" \n\nHowever, \"hairs\" is used when referring to individual strands of hair, as in \"I found two hairs on my shirt.\" In this case, it emphasizes the countable aspect of individual strands. So, both forms are correct when used appropriately, depending on whether you're talking about hair as a whole or individual strands.",
